   NASA CalTech JPL Robotics

                            Machine Vision Group
     __________________________________________________________________

       This page contains images; a text-only page is also available.
     __________________________________________________________________

   JPL's Machine Vision group provides the Laboratory with expert
   knowledge about imaging sensors and automated image interpretation in
   many domains; high-speed target tracking, robotic self-localization,
   passive stereo range imaging, and precision landing and landing hazard
   avoidance for smart spacecraft at Mars and small bodies to name a few.
   The group provides vision processing both for space missions (like the
   1997 Mars Pathfinder, the 2003 MER Rovers, and the 2007 Smart Lander)
   and Earth-based robot platforms (research rovers, Chornobyl inspection,
   and unmanned ground vehicles).
     __________________________________________________________________

  Ongoing Tasks

   People from the MV group are involved with many ongoing research tasks:
     Distributed Optical Sensor-Based Control for In-Situ Exploration
     FIDO Exploration Technology Rover
     Ladar Analysis for Unmanned Ground Vehicles
     Learning Terrain Classification for Cross-Country Autonomous
       Navigation
     Mars 2003 Exploration Rovers
     Mars 2007 Smart Lander ATD: Entry Descent and Landing
     Multi-resolution Mapping Using Surface, Descent, and Orbital Imagery
     Onboard 3D Model Generation of Rock Surfaces
     TMR: Tactical Mobile Robot
     Visual Methods for Small Body Exploration

  Previous Work

     Long Range Science Rover
     Obstacle Detection for Automated Mowing Operations
     Onboard Science Processing and Buffer Management for Smarter Deep
       Space Communications
     Ordnance Recognition
     Pioneer - Inspection of the Chornobyl Nuclear Facility
     Planetary Dexterous Manipulation
